WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:23.000
G-dep presents The Secret Garden by Francis Hodgson Bannette.
  
01:45.000 --> 01:54.000
When Mary was nine years old, she woke up one hot morning and felt that there was something wrong.

01:54.000 --> 02:03.000
She heard strange cries and shouts and the sound of feet outside her door, but no one came to see her.

02:03.000 --> 02:09.000
She went back to sleep.

02:10.000 --> 02:18.000
Later, when Mary woke up, the house was silent. She heard nothing.

02:18.000 --> 02:24.000
Mary was angry because no one came to bring her food or to dress her.

02:24.000 --> 02:34.000
Suddenly her door opened and two Englishmen entered. Mary looked at them angrily.

02:35.000 --> 02:42.000
Why has everyone forgotten me? She asked. Where is my eye? Why does no one come?

02:42.000 --> 02:47.000
Poor little kid. Said one of the men. There is nobody here.

02:47.000 --> 02:56.000
That is how Mary discovered that her mother and father were dead and that the servants were dead too because of a terrible disease.

02:56.000 --> 03:05.000
That was why the house was so silent. Mary Lennox was completely alone.

03:05.000 --> 03:13.000
There was no one in India to look after Mary, so she went to England to live with her uncle, Mr. Craven,

03:13.000 --> 03:20.000
who lived in a big house in Yorkshire called Misulfweight Manor.

03:20.000 --> 03:25.000
Mrs. Medlock, her uncle's housekeeper, met Mary in London.

03:25.000 --> 03:35.000
Mary disliked Mrs. Medlock immediately, but this was nothing new because Mary disliked everyone.

03:35.000 --> 03:46.000
Mrs. Medlock did not like Mary. She thought that the little girl was bad-tempered, rude and plain and she was right.

03:46.000 --> 03:54.000
During the long train journey to Yorkshire, Mrs. Medlock told Mary about the house where she was going to live.

03:54.000 --> 04:00.000
It seemed very large and gloomy and it was near the edge of a moor.

04:00.000 --> 04:09.000
There's nothing for you to do there and your uncle is not interested in you, said Mrs. Medlock. He's got a crooked back.

04:09.000 --> 04:13.000
He was a sour young man until he married.

04:13.000 --> 04:19.000
Mary listened more carefully now. She did not know that her uncle was married.

04:19.000 --> 04:23.000
His wife was very pretty and he loved her very much.

04:23.000 --> 04:28.000
When she died, he became even stranger. Mrs. Medlock said,

04:28.000 --> 04:30.000
Oh, did she die?

04:30.000 --> 04:39.000
Asked Mary, yes, and now he likes nobody. He's away most of the time, so you must look after yourself.

04:44.000 --> 04:48.000
It was dark and raining when they got out of the train.

04:48.000 --> 04:57.000
They travelled to the house by horse and carriage, but Mary could see nothing outside because of the rain and the darkness of the night.

04:57.000 --> 04:59.000
What is the moor? Mary asked.

04:59.000 --> 05:04.000
It's miles and miles of land, replied Mrs. Medlock.

05:04.000 --> 05:10.000
Very little grows on it and nothing lives on it, except ponies and sheep.

05:11.000 --> 05:14.000
The carriage stopped at last in a courtyard.

05:17.000 --> 05:20.000
A butler opened a heavy wooden door.

05:23.000 --> 05:27.000
Take her to her room. He said to Mrs. Medlock.

05:27.000 --> 05:32.000
The master doesn't want to see her. He's going to London tomorrow.

05:33.000 --> 05:41.000
Mrs. Medlock took Mary upstairs, along many corridors to a room with a fire burning in it and food on the table.

05:41.000 --> 05:47.000
Well, here you are, said Mrs. Medlock. This is where you'll live.

05:47.000 --> 05:55.000
This room and the next is where you must stay. You can't go into the other parts of the house. Don't forget that.

05:55.000 --> 06:00.000
Mary Lennox felt terribly alone.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.000
Chapter 2

06:06.000 --> 06:10.000
Mary visits the gardens.

06:10.000 --> 06:17.000
The next morning, Mary woke up when a young housemaid came into her room to light the fire.

06:17.000 --> 06:23.000
Her name was Martha, and she talked to Mary while she worked.

06:23.000 --> 06:27.000
Mary didn't understand servants who were friendly.

06:28.000 --> 06:37.000
In India, she had spoken to servants only to give them orders. She never said, please or thank you.

06:37.000 --> 06:43.000
Once, she had even slapped her eye as face when she was angry with her.

06:43.000 --> 06:49.000
Somehow, she knew that she must not behave in this way with Martha.

06:50.000 --> 07:01.000
At first, Mary did not listen to Martha. But after a while, she began to like the sound of the friendly Yorkshire voice.

07:01.000 --> 07:07.000
You should see all my little brothers and sisters in our little cottage on the moor, Martha said.

07:07.000 --> 07:12.000
There's twelve of us, and my father only earns sixteen shillings a week.

07:12.000 --> 07:18.000
It is hard for my mother to feed them all. The fresh air on the moor makes them strong and healthy.

07:18.000 --> 07:27.000
Our dickens twelve. He's always out in the moor. He's good with animals. He's tamed a wild pony.

07:27.000 --> 07:35.000
Go and look at the gardens, Martha said. There's not much growing now, but they're lovely in summer.

07:35.000 --> 07:40.000
She paused for a moment, and then said quietly.

07:40.000 --> 07:44.000
One of the gardens is locked up. No one has been in it for ten years.

07:44.000 --> 07:45.000
Why?

07:45.000 --> 07:48.000
Asked Mary.

07:48.000 --> 07:58.000
Mr. Craven closed it after his wife died. It was her garden. He locked the door, dug a hole and buried the key.

07:58.000 --> 08:05.000
The enormous grounds of mistlethweight manner were divided by high walls into many gardens.

08:05.000 --> 08:15.000
In some there were flowers, trees and fountains. Vegetables grew in others. Doors opened from garden into garden.

08:15.000 --> 08:21.000
Because it was winter, the trees were bare and no flowers grew.

08:21.000 --> 08:27.000
Mary thought that it all looked very empty and ugly.

08:27.000 --> 08:31.000
After a while, an old man came through one of the doors.

08:31.000 --> 08:37.000
He had a surly old face and did not seem at all pleased to see Mary.

08:37.000 --> 08:40.000
Can I go through that door? Mary asked.

08:40.000 --> 08:42.000
If you like.

08:42.000 --> 08:43.000
He replied.

08:43.000 --> 08:46.000
There's nothing to see.

08:46.000 --> 08:51.000
Mary hoped that she might find the door to the locked garden.

08:51.000 --> 08:56.000
She tried many doors, but they all opened easily.

08:56.000 --> 09:03.000
Then she noticed one wall that was covered in ivy, but seemed to have no door in it.

09:03.000 --> 09:08.000
She could see tall trees behind the ivy covered wall.

09:08.000 --> 09:13.000
A robin on a high branch started to sing.

09:13.000 --> 09:21.000
She stopped to listen, and the little bird with the red breast seemed almost to be calling to her.

09:21.000 --> 09:29.000
His cheerful song brought a small smile to her sad face.

09:29.000 --> 09:31.000
The old man continued digging.

09:31.000 --> 09:35.000
He ignored Mary until at last she said.

09:35.000 --> 09:38.000
There's a garden over there without a door.

09:38.000 --> 09:39.000
What garden?

09:39.000 --> 09:41.000
He asked angrily.

09:41.000 --> 09:43.000
On the other side of the wall?

09:43.000 --> 09:44.000
She answered.

09:44.000 --> 09:48.000
I saw a robin in the trees over there.

09:48.000 --> 09:54.000
The old man stopped digging, and to Mary's surprise, he smiled.

09:54.000 --> 09:58.000
He looked quite different when he smiled.

09:58.000 --> 10:04.000
He whistled very softly.

10:04.000 --> 10:08.000
Then a wonderful thing happened.

10:08.000 --> 10:14.000
There was a sound of wings, and the robin came down next to the man's foot.

10:14.000 --> 10:15.000
Here he is.

10:15.000 --> 10:18.000
The old man chuckled.

10:18.000 --> 10:22.000
He always comes to me when I whistle.

10:22.000 --> 10:25.000
Isn't he a nice little bird?

10:25.000 --> 10:29.000
The robin hopped about, pecking at the earth.

10:29.000 --> 10:33.000
The gardener, Ben Weatherstaff, continued digging.

10:33.000 --> 10:36.000
He's the only friend I've got.

10:36.000 --> 10:37.000
He said.

10:37.000 --> 10:39.000
I've never had any friends.

10:39.000 --> 10:42.000
Said Mary, sadly.

10:42.000 --> 10:45.000
Ben stopped digging and looked at Mary.

10:45.000 --> 10:47.000
You and I are the same then.

10:47.000 --> 10:49.000
He said to her.

10:49.000 --> 10:54.000
We're not good looking and we're as sour as we'll look.

10:54.000 --> 11:01.000
It was the first time that Mary had ever thought about her angry face and bad temper.

11:01.000 --> 11:06.000
Now that she did, she felt uncomfortable.

11:06.000 --> 11:12.000
Just then, the clear sound of the robin song made her look towards the apple tree where

11:12.000 --> 11:14.000
he sat.

11:14.000 --> 11:19.000
Ben Weatherstaff laughed.

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
What did he do that for?

11:22.000 --> 11:23.000
Asked Mary.

11:23.000 --> 11:26.000
He's decided to be your friend.

11:26.000 --> 11:27.000
Replied Ben.

11:27.000 --> 11:29.000
He's taken a fancy to you.

11:29.000 --> 11:30.000
To me.

11:30.000 --> 11:32.000
Said Mary.

11:32.000 --> 11:36.000
He moved softly towards the little tree and looked up.

11:36.000 --> 11:38.000
Would you make friends with me?

11:38.000 --> 11:43.000
She said gently to the robin as if she was speaking to a person.

11:43.000 --> 11:44.000
Why?

11:44.000 --> 11:46.000
Said Ben quietly.

11:46.000 --> 11:51.000
You said that like a real child instead of a little old woman.

11:51.000 --> 11:57.000
You said it almost like digging when he talks to his wild things out on the moor.

11:57.000 --> 12:00.000
The robin flew over the wall.

12:00.000 --> 12:02.000
There must be a door to that garden.

12:02.000 --> 12:04.000
Mary said firmly.

12:04.000 --> 12:07.000
There's no door that you can find.

12:07.000 --> 12:11.000
And in any case, it's none of your business.

12:11.000 --> 12:13.000
Ben said sharply.

12:13.000 --> 12:18.000
Don't poke your nose in where it doesn't belong.

12:18.000 --> 12:25.000
The gardener walked away without saying goodbye.

12:25.000 --> 12:27.000
Chapter Three.

12:27.000 --> 12:31.000
A cry in the night.

12:31.000 --> 12:36.000
Mary spent most of her days outside in the grounds.

12:36.000 --> 12:39.000
The cold wind made her cheeks pink.

12:39.000 --> 12:43.000
And each evening she ate all of her food.

12:43.000 --> 12:48.000
After dinner, she liked to sit near the fire and talk to Martha.

12:48.000 --> 12:51.000
Why does Mr Craven hate the locked garden?

12:51.000 --> 12:54.000
Mary asked once.

12:55.000 --> 12:57.000
It was Mrs Craven's garden.

12:57.000 --> 12:58.000
She loved it.

12:58.000 --> 13:02.000
She and Mr Craven looked after the flowers together.

13:02.000 --> 13:04.000
No gardeners were allowed in.

13:04.000 --> 13:06.000
But what happened?

13:06.000 --> 13:09.000
Mary asked impatiently.

13:09.000 --> 13:13.000
Mrs Craven was sitting on a branch of a tree when it broke and she fell.

13:13.000 --> 13:16.000
She was injured so badly she died.

13:16.000 --> 13:19.000
That's why Mr Craven hates the garden.

13:19.000 --> 13:23.000
He won't let anyone ever talk about it.

13:23.000 --> 13:26.000
Mary had never felt sorry for anyone before.

13:26.000 --> 13:32.000
But now she realized how unhappy her uncle must be.

13:32.000 --> 13:38.000
The wind moaned around the house, banging at the doors and windows.

13:38.000 --> 13:42.000
Martha said it was bothering.

13:42.000 --> 13:49.000
Mary listened and through the noise she thought that she heard a child crying.

13:49.000 --> 13:51.000
Do you hear someone crying?

13:51.000 --> 13:53.000
She asked Martha.

13:53.000 --> 13:56.000
Martha suddenly looked confused.

13:56.000 --> 13:59.000
No, she answered.

13:59.000 --> 14:02.000
It's only the wind or the scullery made.

14:02.000 --> 14:05.000
She's cried all day with too thick.

14:05.000 --> 14:10.000
Then Martha quickly left the room.

14:10.000 --> 14:12.000
Next day it rained.

14:12.000 --> 14:18.000
Mary was bored and complained to Martha that she had nothing to do.

14:18.000 --> 14:22.000
On a day like this at home we all try to keep busy indoors.

14:22.000 --> 14:24.000
Martha said.

14:24.000 --> 14:26.000
Except Dickon.

14:26.000 --> 14:29.000
He goes out on the moor in all types of weather.

14:29.000 --> 14:32.000
He brought home a fox cub that he found.

14:32.000 --> 14:35.000
He's got a crow too called suit.

14:39.000 --> 14:44.000
When Martha left her alone, Mary decided to explore the house.

14:44.000 --> 14:49.000
She went along corridors and up and down stairs.

14:49.000 --> 14:57.000
In the silence of the house she heard again the sound of a child crying.

14:57.000 --> 15:00.000
She stopped to listen at a door.

15:00.000 --> 15:05.000
But then another door opened and out came Mrs Medlock.

15:05.000 --> 15:07.000
What are you doing here?

15:07.000 --> 15:11.000
She said and she took Mary by the arm and pulled her away.

15:11.000 --> 15:13.000
Get back to your room at once.

15:13.000 --> 15:17.000
I didn't know which way to go and then I heard someone crying.

15:17.000 --> 15:19.000
Said Mary.

15:19.000 --> 15:22.000
You didn't hear anything, said Mrs Medlock.

15:22.000 --> 15:27.000
Go back to your room or I'll tell the master that you disobeyed him.

15:27.000 --> 15:30.000
Mary was angry.

15:30.000 --> 15:33.000
She wanted to know what the cry was.

15:33.000 --> 15:37.000
Soon the storm passed.

15:37.000 --> 15:42.000
Wait until the sun shines and lights up the moor, said Martha.

15:42.000 --> 15:46.000
I'd love to see your cottage on the moor and to meet your mother.

15:46.000 --> 15:48.000
Said Mary.

15:48.000 --> 15:51.000
You would like my mother, Martha said.

15:51.000 --> 15:54.000
She's kind and good tempered and works hard.

15:54.000 --> 15:59.000
When it's my day off and I can go home and see her, I'd jump for joy.

15:59.000 --> 16:01.000
I'd like to see Dickon too.

16:01.000 --> 16:02.000
Said Mary.

16:02.000 --> 16:05.000
Yes, you'd like him, Martha said.

16:05.000 --> 16:07.000
Everyone likes Dickon.

16:07.000 --> 16:09.000
No one likes me.

16:09.000 --> 16:11.000
Said Mary, sadly.

16:11.000 --> 16:14.000
Maybe that's because you don't like yourself?

16:14.000 --> 16:16.000
Laughed Martha.

16:16.000 --> 16:18.000
I never thought of that.

16:18.000 --> 16:20.000
Said Mary.

16:20.000 --> 16:24.000
Mary found Ben Weatherstaff working in the garden.

16:24.000 --> 16:26.000
Springs come in.

16:26.000 --> 16:27.000
He said.

16:27.000 --> 16:30.000
The plants are growing under the soil.

16:30.000 --> 16:35.000
Soon you'll see crocuses and daffodils.

16:35.000 --> 16:40.000
Mary saw that the robin was on a wall covered with ivy.

16:40.000 --> 16:44.000
He hopped down to the soil at her feet.

16:44.000 --> 16:48.000
The robin tried to find a worm in the garden.

16:48.000 --> 16:53.000
Suddenly Mary saw an old, rusty key.

16:53.000 --> 16:56.000
Perhaps it's been buried for ten years.

16:56.000 --> 16:57.000
She said to herself.

16:57.000 --> 17:00.000
Perhaps it's the key to the garden.

17:00.000 --> 17:04.000
She thought, putting it into her pocket.

17:04.000 --> 17:09.000
After supper, Martha told Mary all about her day at home.

17:10.000 --> 17:12.000
Mother has sent you a present?

17:12.000 --> 17:13.000
She said.

17:13.000 --> 17:19.000
She brought out a skipping rope with striped handles and showed Mary how to skip.

17:19.000 --> 17:21.000
Your mother is very kind.

17:21.000 --> 17:23.000
Mary said.

17:23.000 --> 17:30.000
She wondered how Mary's mother could find the money to buy her the rope with all those hungry mouths to feed.

17:30.000 --> 17:37.000
Mary skipped all the time and the more she skipped, the stronger she grew.

17:37.000 --> 17:44.000
Her cheeks became red and her plain face started to look almost pretty.

17:44.000 --> 17:51.000
One day, as Mary watched the robin in the garden, a wonderful thing happened.

17:51.000 --> 17:55.000
To Mary, it was almost like magic.

17:55.000 --> 18:05.000
A small gust of wind blew aside some of the ivy on the wall and beneath the leaves, she saw a door.

18:05.000 --> 18:09.000
She remembered that she had the key in her pocket.

18:09.000 --> 18:16.000
She tried it in the lock, and although it was very stiff, she turned it.

18:19.000 --> 18:27.000
The next moment, she stood inside the secret garden.

18:27.000 --> 18:34.000
It was the loveliest and most mysterious looking place that Mary had seen.

18:34.000 --> 18:42.000
It was overgrown and untidy, but she could see plants starting to push their way up through the soil.

18:42.000 --> 18:47.000
She pulled weeds away to make space for the spring flowers to grow.

18:47.000 --> 18:49.000
Now they look as if they can breathe.

18:49.000 --> 18:50.000
She thought.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
Then she whispered to herself.

18:53.000 --> 18:59.000
I am the first person who has spoken in here for ten years.

18:59.000 --> 19:04.000
Time passed quickly as Mary cleared the weeds and dead grass.

19:04.000 --> 19:09.000
Soon it was time to go back to the house for her supper.

19:09.000 --> 19:16.000
Mary wanted to tell Martha her secret, but she knew that this was not a good idea.

19:16.000 --> 19:22.000
She might be forbidden to go into the secret garden again, so instead she said,

19:22.000 --> 19:25.000
I would like a little garden to grow things in.

19:25.000 --> 19:29.000
Why, that's just what you need to keep you busy, said Martha.

19:29.000 --> 19:35.000
I'll get Dickon to bring some garden tools and some seeds to plant.

19:35.000 --> 19:40.000
Mary worked with her hands each day in the secret garden.

19:40.000 --> 19:45.000
She was careful not to let Ben Weatherstaff see where she went.

19:45.000 --> 19:48.000
But Ben noticed a change in her.

19:48.000 --> 19:50.000
One day, he said,

19:50.000 --> 19:53.000
The fresher is good for you.

19:53.000 --> 19:58.000
You're less thin, and your skin is less yellow.

20:00.000 --> 20:04.000
Chapter 4, Dickon.

20:04.000 --> 20:09.000
One day, Mary saw a boy sitting under a tree.

20:09.000 --> 20:12.000
He seemed about twelve years old.

20:12.000 --> 20:15.000
He played on a pipe.

20:15.000 --> 20:19.000
Two rabbits and a squirrel were near him.

20:19.000 --> 20:23.000
They seemed to listen to the tune he played.

20:27.000 --> 20:32.000
The boy got up carefully because he didn't want to frighten the animals.

20:32.000 --> 20:36.000
He had blue eyes and a round pink face.

20:36.000 --> 20:38.000
I'm Dickon.

20:38.000 --> 20:43.000
He said to Mary, I brought the garden tools and some flower seeds.

20:43.000 --> 20:50.000
Dickon had a kind and gentle smile and Mary felt that she knew him quite well.

20:50.000 --> 20:56.000
She felt that if the wild animals could trust him, then she could trust him too.

20:56.000 --> 20:58.000
Do you know about the secret garden?

20:58.000 --> 20:59.000
Asked Mary.

20:59.000 --> 21:01.000
I've heard about it.

21:01.000 --> 21:02.000
Dickon answered.

21:02.000 --> 21:04.000
But I don't know where it is.

21:04.000 --> 21:05.000
Come with me.

21:05.000 --> 21:07.000
Mary said.

21:07.000 --> 21:10.000
Mary was careful that no one saw them.

21:10.000 --> 21:14.000
And then she took Dickon through the door in the wall.

21:14.000 --> 21:16.000
Dickon was very surprised.

21:16.000 --> 21:19.000
This is a strange, pretty place.

21:19.000 --> 21:20.000
He said.

21:20.000 --> 21:23.000
It's like being in a dream.

21:23.000 --> 21:29.000
Dickon looked around at all the plants and trees which Mary thought were dead.

21:29.000 --> 21:31.000
All of these will grow.

21:31.000 --> 21:32.000
He said.

21:32.000 --> 21:37.000
There will be flowers and roses everywhere in a few weeks.

21:38.000 --> 21:44.000
Dickon and Mary worked together to clear away the weeds and dead wood.

21:44.000 --> 21:49.000
Mary felt that she had never known anyone like Dickon.

21:49.000 --> 21:55.000
She tried to speak in a warm, friendly voice like Dickon's and Martha's.

21:55.000 --> 21:56.000
Do you like me?

21:56.000 --> 21:57.000
She asked.

21:57.000 --> 21:58.000
Yes, I do.

21:58.000 --> 22:00.000
He laughed.

22:00.000 --> 22:03.000
The Rubble likes you too.

22:03.000 --> 22:09.000
That evening, after dinner, Mrs. Medlock took Mary to see Mr. Craven.

22:09.000 --> 22:15.000
He's going abroad tomorrow and he wants to see you first, she said.

22:15.000 --> 22:18.000
Mary felt a little afraid.

22:18.000 --> 22:25.000
She felt sure that she would not like Mr. Craven and that he would not like her.

22:25.000 --> 22:32.000
But she found that Mr. Craven wasn't really frightening and that his back wasn't really crooked.

22:33.000 --> 22:38.000
His face was handsome, but he looked sad and worried.

22:38.000 --> 22:43.000
He asked Mary if there was anything that she would like.

22:43.000 --> 22:48.000
Mary asked for a piece of garden in which to grow her own flowers.

22:48.000 --> 22:50.000
Of course.

22:50.000 --> 22:51.000
Set her uncle.

22:51.000 --> 22:54.000
You may take any bit that is not used.

22:54.000 --> 22:57.000
Mary was delighted.

22:57.000 --> 23:01.000
Now she could have the secret garden for herself.

23:01.000 --> 23:07.000
That same night, Mary was awakened by the wind roaring around the house.

23:07.000 --> 23:09.000
She couldn't sleep.

23:09.000 --> 23:14.000
And as she lay in bed, she heard the crying noise again.

23:18.000 --> 23:19.000
That's not the wind.

23:19.000 --> 23:20.000
She thought.

23:20.000 --> 23:24.000
I'm going to find out where that noise is coming from.

23:24.000 --> 23:29.000
Mary took a candle to light her way along the dark corridors.

23:29.000 --> 23:34.000
Suddenly, she noticed a light from under one of the doors.

23:34.000 --> 23:41.000
The crying sound came from behind the door and Mary knew that it was a child.

23:41.000 --> 23:52.000
She gently opened the door and saw that a young boy lay on the bed crying.

23:52.000 --> 23:56.000
When the boy saw Mary, he stopped crying at once.

23:56.000 --> 23:58.000
Are you a ghost?

23:58.000 --> 23:59.000
He asked.

23:59.000 --> 24:01.000
He looked very frightened.

24:01.000 --> 24:02.000
No.

24:02.000 --> 24:03.000
I'm Mary Lennox.

24:03.000 --> 24:04.000
She answered.

24:04.000 --> 24:06.000
Who are you?

24:09.000 --> 24:11.000
Chapter 5.

24:11.000 --> 24:12.000
Colin.

24:13.000 --> 24:14.000
I'm Colin.

24:14.000 --> 24:16.000
Mr. Cravenson.

24:16.000 --> 24:17.000
Said the boy.

24:17.000 --> 24:19.000
Then I must be your cousin.

24:19.000 --> 24:20.000
Mary said.

24:20.000 --> 24:22.000
Don't you know that I came to live here?

24:22.000 --> 24:23.000
No.

24:23.000 --> 24:24.000
He answered.

24:24.000 --> 24:25.000
No one told me.

24:25.000 --> 24:26.000
Why?

24:26.000 --> 24:27.000
Asked Mary.

24:27.000 --> 24:30.000
Because I am afraid that people will see me.

24:30.000 --> 24:33.000
I won't let people see me and talk about me.

24:33.000 --> 24:34.000
Why?

24:34.000 --> 24:36.000
Asked Mary.

24:36.000 --> 24:40.000
She felt more puzzled with each moment that passed.

24:40.000 --> 24:44.000
Because I'm always ill and I must stay in bed.

24:44.000 --> 24:47.000
The servants are not allowed to speak about me.

24:47.000 --> 24:50.000
My father won't let anyone mention me.

24:50.000 --> 24:53.000
He's afraid I'll grow up to have a crooked back.

24:54.000 --> 24:58.000
My father hates me because my mother died when I was born.

24:58.000 --> 25:00.000
Have you always been here?

25:00.000 --> 25:01.000
Asked Mary.

25:01.000 --> 25:02.000
Nearly always.

25:02.000 --> 25:03.000
Said Colin.

25:03.000 --> 25:07.000
If I go out, people stare at me and I hate it.

25:07.000 --> 25:09.000
If you don't like people to see you.

25:09.000 --> 25:10.000
Mary said.

25:10.000 --> 25:11.000
Shall I go away?

25:11.000 --> 25:12.000
Oh no.

25:12.000 --> 25:14.000
Colin replied quickly.

25:14.000 --> 25:16.000
You must stay and talk to me.

25:17.000 --> 25:22.000
Mary put her candle down on a table near the bed and sat on a chair.

25:24.000 --> 25:27.000
They talked for a long time.

25:27.000 --> 25:33.000
Colin wanted to know all about Mary and about her life at Misselthwaite.

25:33.000 --> 25:40.000
He told her how unhappy and lonely he was, even though he was given anything that he wanted.

25:40.000 --> 25:43.000
Everyone must do as I say.

25:43.000 --> 25:44.000
Colin said.

25:44.000 --> 25:46.000
I will be ill if they don't.

25:46.000 --> 25:48.000
Do you think you will get well?

25:48.000 --> 25:49.000
Mary asked.

25:49.000 --> 25:51.000
I don't suppose I will.

25:51.000 --> 25:52.000
Colin answered.

25:52.000 --> 25:55.000
No one believes I will live until I grow up.

25:55.000 --> 25:58.000
Let's talk about something else.

25:58.000 --> 25:59.000
How old are you?

25:59.000 --> 26:01.000
I'm ten, like you.

26:01.000 --> 26:02.000
Mary said.

26:02.000 --> 26:04.000
How do you know I'm ten?

26:04.000 --> 26:05.000
He asked.

26:05.000 --> 26:09.000
Because when you were born, your father locked the garden door and buried the key.

26:09.000 --> 26:11.000
It's been locked for ten years.

26:11.000 --> 26:12.000
Mary answered.

26:12.000 --> 26:13.000
What garden?

26:13.000 --> 26:14.000
Colin asked.

26:14.000 --> 26:17.000
It was the garden Mr. Craven hates.

26:17.000 --> 26:19.000
Said Mary, nervously.

26:19.000 --> 26:21.000
He locked the door.

26:21.000 --> 26:23.000
No one knew where he buried the key.

26:23.000 --> 26:25.000
What's the garden like?

26:25.000 --> 26:26.000
Colin persisted.

26:26.000 --> 26:29.000
It's been locked for ten years.

26:29.000 --> 26:31.000
Mary said, carefully.

26:31.000 --> 26:35.000
She did not want him to know that she had found it.

26:35.000 --> 26:37.000
But it was too late to be careful.

26:37.000 --> 26:41.000
Colin was very excited at the idea of a hidden garden.

26:41.000 --> 26:43.000
I will make them open the door.

26:43.000 --> 26:44.000
He said.

26:44.000 --> 26:45.000
Oh no!

26:45.000 --> 26:46.000
Cried Mary.

26:46.000 --> 26:48.000
Let's keep it a secret.

26:48.000 --> 26:52.000
If they open the door, it will never be a secret again.

26:52.000 --> 26:57.000
If we find the door one day, we can go inside and no one will know about it except us.

26:57.000 --> 26:58.000
I would like that.

26:58.000 --> 26:59.000
Said Colin.

26:59.000 --> 27:02.000
I've never had a secret before.

27:02.000 --> 27:04.000
He was tired from talking.

27:04.000 --> 27:10.000
And as he fell asleep, Mary went quietly away.

27:10.000 --> 27:13.000
Chapter 6.

27:13.000 --> 27:16.000
Wet weather.

27:17.000 --> 27:21.000
Next morning, Mary told Martha that she had found Colin.

27:21.000 --> 27:24.000
Martha was very upset.

27:24.000 --> 27:28.000
She thought that she could lose her job for allowing Mary to find the young boy.

27:28.000 --> 27:29.000
Don't worry.

27:29.000 --> 27:30.000
Said Mary.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000
Colin was pleased to see me.

27:33.000 --> 27:35.000
He wants to see me every day.

27:35.000 --> 27:37.000
You must have bewitched him.

27:37.000 --> 27:39.000
Said Martha.

27:39.000 --> 27:41.000
What's the matter with him?

27:41.000 --> 27:43.000
Mary asked.

27:43.000 --> 27:47.000
Martha told Mary that Colin had never been allowed to walk.

27:47.000 --> 27:51.000
His father thought that his back was weak.

27:51.000 --> 27:56.000
Even though a famous doctor had examined him and said that he would get strong if less fuss

27:56.000 --> 28:02.000
was made of him, Colin was still spoiled and allowed to do everything that he wanted.

28:02.000 --> 28:04.000
Colin thinks he will die.

28:04.000 --> 28:07.000
Said Mary.

28:07.000 --> 28:12.000
Mother says that he has no reason to live if he's closed up in his room all the time.

28:13.000 --> 28:15.000
It's good for me to be outside.

28:15.000 --> 28:16.000
Said Mary.

28:16.000 --> 28:18.000
Do you think that it would help Colin?

28:18.000 --> 28:20.000
Oh, I don't know.

28:20.000 --> 28:21.000
Martha said.

28:21.000 --> 28:25.000
He had a bad temper tantrum when he was taken into the garden.

28:25.000 --> 28:29.000
He was upset because he thought one of the gardeners was looking at him.

28:29.000 --> 28:31.000
He cried until he felt ill.

28:31.000 --> 28:35.000
If he ever gets angry with me, I won't go to see him again.

28:35.000 --> 28:37.000
Said Mary.

28:38.000 --> 28:42.000
When Mary next went to see Colin, she told him about Dickon.

28:42.000 --> 28:44.000
He's not like anyone else.

28:44.000 --> 28:45.000
She said.

28:45.000 --> 28:47.000
All the animals on the wall love him.

28:47.000 --> 28:50.000
When he plays his pipe, they come to listen.

28:50.000 --> 28:52.000
The moor must be a wonderful place.

28:52.000 --> 28:53.000
Said Colin.

28:53.000 --> 28:54.000
But I can't go there.

28:54.000 --> 28:56.000
I'm going to die.

28:56.000 --> 28:58.000
How do you know that?

28:58.000 --> 28:59.000
Mary asked.

28:59.000 --> 29:03.000
She felt a little cross with Colin.

29:03.000 --> 29:06.000
He seemed to be pleased with the thought that he could die.

29:07.000 --> 29:09.000
Because everyone says I will die.

29:09.000 --> 29:10.000
Colin replied.

29:10.000 --> 29:13.000
I think that my father will be pleased when I'm dead.

29:13.000 --> 29:14.000
I don't believe that.

29:14.000 --> 29:15.000
Mary said.

29:15.000 --> 29:17.000
The famous doctor was right.

29:17.000 --> 29:21.000
They should make much less fuss of you and allow you to go out.

29:21.000 --> 29:24.000
If you could see Dickon, you'd want to get well.

29:25.000 --> 29:32.000
Then Mary told Colin about Dickon's family, who had no money, but were all healthy and cheerful.

29:33.000 --> 29:38.000
It rained for a week, so Mary could not visit the garden.

29:38.000 --> 29:43.000
Because the weather was so bad, she spent most of her time with Colin.

29:43.000 --> 29:46.000
They read books and talked together.

29:46.000 --> 29:50.000
And for the first time, Mary heard Colin laugh.

29:50.000 --> 29:55.000
Colin often spoke about the secret garden and wondered what was in it.

29:55.000 --> 30:00.000
Mary felt that she could not tell him her secret yet.

30:00.000 --> 30:05.000
So she still did not tell him that she knew where the mysterious garden was.

30:05.000 --> 30:09.000
I'll wait until the rain stops before I decide what to do.

30:09.000 --> 30:11.000
Thought Mary.

30:12.000 --> 30:20.000
On the day that the rain finished, Mary woke up early to find that the sunlight was streaming through her windows.

30:20.000 --> 30:25.000
She went quickly to the secret garden, and she found that Dickon was already there.

30:25.000 --> 30:28.000
I couldn't stay in bed in a morning like this.

30:28.000 --> 30:31.000
He said, look at the garden.

30:31.000 --> 30:37.000
The rain and sunshine had made the new plant start to come through the earth.

30:37.000 --> 30:41.000
There were some purple, orange and gold crocuses.

30:41.000 --> 30:46.000
Mary was very pleased to see them, and she kissed them.

30:46.000 --> 30:48.000
The robin was building a nest.

30:48.000 --> 30:50.000
We mustn't watch too closely.

30:50.000 --> 30:55.000
Dickon said, he'll stay here with us if we don't frighten him.

30:56.000 --> 31:00.000
A whole week had gone by since Mary had seen Dickon.

31:00.000 --> 31:03.000
She told him that she had found Colin.

31:03.000 --> 31:06.000
If he comes out here in the garden, he'll forget that easily.

31:06.000 --> 31:13.000
Dickon said, he'll be another child, looking at the flowers and animals like us.

31:13.000 --> 31:21.000
When Mary went back to the house at the end of the day, Martha told her that Colin was angry because she had not been to see him.

31:21.000 --> 31:26.000
I won't allow that boy to come here if you stay with him instead of me.

31:26.000 --> 31:31.000
Colin said, if you send Dickon away, I'll never come into this room again.

31:31.000 --> 31:33.000
Mary replied, you're selfish.

31:33.000 --> 31:35.000
Colin raged.

31:35.000 --> 31:36.000
What about you?

31:36.000 --> 31:38.000
Mary replied furiously.

31:38.000 --> 31:41.000
You're the most selfish boy I know.

31:41.000 --> 31:43.000
Well, I'm going to die.

31:43.000 --> 31:44.000
Colin said.

31:44.000 --> 31:45.000
No, you're not.

31:45.000 --> 31:46.000
Mary replied.

31:46.000 --> 31:49.000
You just say that to make people feel sorry for you.

31:49.000 --> 31:52.000
But they don't feel sorry. You're too nasty.

31:52.000 --> 31:55.000
Mary marched to the door and then said angrily.

31:55.000 --> 32:01.000
I was going to tell you all about Dickon and his fox and crow, but I won't now.

32:01.000 --> 32:05.000
She slammed the door behind her.

32:05.000 --> 32:11.000
Later, when Mary remembered how lonely Colin was, she felt sorry for him.

32:11.000 --> 32:13.000
I'll go and see him tomorrow.

32:13.000 --> 32:14.000
She thought.

32:14.000 --> 32:16.000
I'll go and sit with him.

32:16.000 --> 32:21.000
Later that night, Mary was awakened by the sound of screaming and crying.

32:21.000 --> 32:25.000
It's Colin having one of his tempers.

32:25.000 --> 32:26.000
She thought.

32:26.000 --> 32:32.000
She put her hands over her ears, but she could not block out the terrible noise.

32:32.000 --> 32:34.000
Someone should stop him.

32:34.000 --> 32:35.000
She cried.

32:35.000 --> 32:38.000
He deserves to be punished for being so selfish.

32:38.000 --> 32:40.000
He's broken everyone in the house.

32:40.000 --> 32:44.000
She ran into Colin's room and shouted at him.

32:44.000 --> 32:47.000
Stop! I hate you. Everyone hates you.

32:47.000 --> 32:53.000
You'll scream until you die and I hope that you do.

32:53.000 --> 32:55.000
Chapter 7.

32:55.000 --> 32:59.000
I will live forever and ever.

32:59.000 --> 33:02.000
Colin looked terrible.

33:02.000 --> 33:08.000
His face was swollen from crying, but Mary was too angry to care.

33:08.000 --> 33:11.000
If you scream again, then I will scream louder.

33:11.000 --> 33:12.000
She told him.

33:12.000 --> 33:14.000
I can't stop.

33:14.000 --> 33:15.000
Colin sobbed.

33:15.000 --> 33:18.000
There's something wrong with my back.

33:18.000 --> 33:21.000
I will have a crooked back and then I will die.

33:21.000 --> 33:24.000
Turn over and let me look at your back.

33:24.000 --> 33:26.000
Mary said.

33:26.000 --> 33:30.000
She looked at the poor, thin back for a long time.

33:30.000 --> 33:32.000
There's nothing wrong with it.

33:32.000 --> 33:34.000
Your back is as straight as mine.

33:34.000 --> 33:36.000
She told him.

33:36.000 --> 33:38.000
Colin stopped crying.

33:38.000 --> 33:45.000
And Mary sat by his bed, talking to him quietly until he fell asleep.

33:45.000 --> 33:51.000
The next morning, Mary met Dickon in the garden and she told him about Colin crying in the night.

33:51.000 --> 33:54.000
We must get him out here, poor boy.

33:54.000 --> 33:56.000
Said Dickon kindly.

33:56.000 --> 33:57.000
Yes, we must.

33:57.000 --> 34:02.000
Said Mary, using the same kind Yorkshire voice.

34:02.000 --> 34:03.000
Dickon laughed.

34:03.000 --> 34:05.000
Talking your Yorkshire voice to Colin.

34:05.000 --> 34:06.000
He said.

34:06.000 --> 34:11.000
It will make him laugh and Mother says laughing is good for people when they're ill.

34:11.000 --> 34:15.000
Mary went to see Colin later that day.

34:15.000 --> 34:21.000
She told him about Dickon and his squirrels who were called Nut and Shell.

34:21.000 --> 34:23.000
Then Colin said.

34:23.000 --> 34:26.000
I'm sorry I said that I would send Dickon away.

34:26.000 --> 34:28.000
He seems a wonderful boy.

34:28.000 --> 34:30.000
I'm glad you said that.

34:30.000 --> 34:31.000
Said Mary.

34:31.000 --> 34:34.000
Because he's coming to see you and he's bringing his animals.

34:35.000 --> 34:38.000
Colin suddenly looked cheerful.

34:38.000 --> 34:44.000
He looked so happy that Mary thought that she would tell him her great secret.

34:44.000 --> 34:45.000
That's not all.

34:45.000 --> 34:46.000
She said.

34:46.000 --> 34:48.000
There's something even better.

34:48.000 --> 34:50.000
I found the door to the garden.

34:50.000 --> 34:53.000
Colin was very pleased.

34:53.000 --> 34:56.000
Then we can go in and find out what's inside.

34:56.000 --> 34:58.000
He cried.

34:58.000 --> 35:02.000
Mary waited for a moment and then she told him the truth.

35:02.000 --> 35:03.000
I've been inside.

35:03.000 --> 35:06.000
That's why I could tell you so much about it.

35:06.000 --> 35:10.000
I couldn't tell you my secret until I was sure that I could trust you.

35:10.000 --> 35:13.000
At breakfast Colin told his nurse.

35:13.000 --> 35:16.000
A boy and his animals are coming to see me.

35:16.000 --> 35:20.000
Bring them straight up when they arrive.

35:20.000 --> 35:23.000
Soon afterwards Mary heard a bleating.

35:23.000 --> 35:27.000
That's Dickon's lamb.

35:27.000 --> 35:28.000
She said.

35:28.000 --> 35:30.000
They're coming.

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
Dickon came in.

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
He was smiling.

35:34.000 --> 35:38.000
He carried a lamb and his little fox followed behind him.

35:38.000 --> 35:42.000
The squirrel sat on one shoulder and the crow on the other.

35:42.000 --> 35:45.000
The other squirrel was in his pocket.

35:45.000 --> 35:49.000
Colin stared in surprise.

35:49.000 --> 35:54.000
Dickon gave the lamb to Colin and handed him a bottle to feed it.

35:54.000 --> 35:57.000
The little boy was busy and happy.

35:57.000 --> 35:59.000
After a while Colin cried.

35:59.000 --> 36:01.000
I must see it all.

36:01.000 --> 36:03.000
I must see the secret garden.

36:03.000 --> 36:05.000
Yes, of course you must.

36:05.000 --> 36:06.000
Said Mary.

36:06.000 --> 36:09.000
And you must lose no time about it.

36:09.000 --> 36:15.000
They put Colin in his wheelchair and Dickon pushed it along the garden paths.

36:15.000 --> 36:21.000
Mary told Colin all about the places they passed on their way to the door that led to the secret garden.

36:21.000 --> 36:23.000
Here's where I met Ben Weatherstaff.

36:23.000 --> 36:24.000
She said.

36:24.000 --> 36:26.000
And this is where I saw the Robin.

36:26.000 --> 36:29.000
Then she said quietly to him.

36:29.000 --> 36:32.000
This is a secret garden.

36:32.000 --> 36:36.000
Mary looked around to make sure that no one was watching.

36:36.000 --> 36:41.000
And then Dickon pushed the chair quickly inside.

36:41.000 --> 36:45.000
Colin looked at the trees and flowers.

36:45.000 --> 36:49.000
He listened to the sweet sound of the bird singing.

36:49.000 --> 36:53.000
And he felt the warm sun on his face.

36:54.000 --> 37:01.000
His pale skin started to become pink as he breathed in the good fresh air.

37:01.000 --> 37:03.000
Then he cried out.

37:03.000 --> 37:07.000
I will be well. I will live forever and ever.

37:07.000 --> 37:11.000
That day, the world changed for Colin.

37:11.000 --> 37:13.000
It's been a wonderful day.

37:13.000 --> 37:14.000
Said Dickon.

37:14.000 --> 37:15.000
It certainly has.

37:15.000 --> 37:16.000
Replied Mary.

37:16.000 --> 37:17.000
Do you think?

37:17.000 --> 37:18.000
Said Colin.

37:18.000 --> 37:21.000
That it was made like this just for me.

37:22.000 --> 37:24.000
You've found almost as Yorkshire as Dickon now.

37:24.000 --> 37:25.000
Laughed Mary.

37:25.000 --> 37:29.000
I don't want this day to finish, but I will come back every day.

37:29.000 --> 37:31.000
Colin said.

37:34.000 --> 37:38.000
Chapter 8. Magic.

37:38.000 --> 37:40.000
Of course she will.

37:40.000 --> 37:41.000
Said Dickon.

37:41.000 --> 37:43.000
She will have you working and walking.

37:43.000 --> 37:50.000
But suddenly, Ben Weatherstaff's angry face looked down at them from the top of the wall.

37:50.000 --> 37:52.000
What are you doing in there?

37:52.000 --> 37:55.000
He shouted angrily at Mary.

37:55.000 --> 38:00.000
Then he saw Colin and his mouth opened in astonishment.

38:00.000 --> 38:02.000
Do you know who I am?

38:02.000 --> 38:03.000
Colin asked.

38:03.000 --> 38:06.000
Yes. Of course I do.

38:06.000 --> 38:07.000
Ben answered.

38:07.000 --> 38:10.000
You are the poor boy who is always ill.

38:10.000 --> 38:12.000
Colin sat up angrily.

38:12.000 --> 38:15.000
There's nothing wrong with me. I'll show you.

38:15.000 --> 38:17.000
He cried.

38:17.000 --> 38:23.000
He pulled himself up out of his chair and with Dickon's help he stood up straight and tall.

38:23.000 --> 38:24.000
Look at me.

38:24.000 --> 38:25.000
He shouted at Ben.

38:25.000 --> 38:27.000
Just look at me.

38:27.000 --> 38:29.000
You dear boy.

38:29.000 --> 38:30.000
Said Ben.

38:30.000 --> 38:33.000
And he cried with happiness.

38:33.000 --> 38:36.000
Colin stayed standing.

38:36.000 --> 38:40.000
Suddenly he felt all his fears leave him.

38:40.000 --> 38:42.000
I'm not afraid anymore.

38:42.000 --> 38:43.000
He cried.

38:43.000 --> 38:45.000
It's the magic of the secret garden.

38:45.000 --> 38:50.000
The magic that made all the plants grow strong has made me grow strong too.

38:50.000 --> 38:55.000
That evening, when Colin sat with Mary, he was quiet.

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000
I'm not going to be a poor, sad boy anymore.

38:58.000 --> 39:04.000
If I believe that I will be stronger and well, then the magic will make it happen.

39:04.000 --> 39:10.000
The next day, when the children went into the garden, Colin told Dickon and Mary to watch him.

39:10.000 --> 39:13.000
I'm going to show you that the magic made me well.

39:13.000 --> 39:20.000
He said, carefully taking a few steps at a time, Colin walked around the garden.

39:20.000 --> 39:23.000
His face glowed with joy.

39:23.000 --> 39:25.000
Please keep this a secret.

39:25.000 --> 39:31.000
He said, when I can walk and run really well, I will walk into my father's study and say,

39:31.000 --> 39:36.000
here I am as well and strong as any boy in Yorkshire.

39:36.000 --> 39:40.000
It was not easy to keep Colin's secret.

39:40.000 --> 39:46.000
The magic garden made Colin's eyes shine and his pale face become pink.

39:46.000 --> 39:55.000
Each day, Colin and Mary did exercises to make them strong and soon they were happier and healthier.

39:55.000 --> 39:59.000
Mary looked pretty and Colin didn't look ill anymore.

39:59.000 --> 40:04.000
Everyone who knew them wondered about the change.

40:04.000 --> 40:11.000
At the time that the secret garden made its magic for Colin, Mr. Craven travelled in distant countries.

40:11.000 --> 40:17.000
For ten years he had tried to run away from his sorrow and nothing could comfort him.

40:17.000 --> 40:24.000
Then, one day while he walked in Austria, he sat down by a stream.

40:24.000 --> 40:29.000
He felt his mind and his body start to relax.

40:29.000 --> 40:34.000
The gentle sound of the running water filled him with peace.

40:34.000 --> 40:39.000
And suddenly he was both healthy and happy.

40:42.000 --> 40:48.000
That same night he dreamt about his wife's garden at Misselthwaite Manor.

40:48.000 --> 40:52.000
The dream made him decide to return home at once.

40:52.000 --> 40:56.000
As soon as he arrived home he went to the garden.

40:56.000 --> 41:05.000
As he walked slowly towards the door of the secret garden all his sadness came rushing back to him.

41:05.000 --> 41:13.000
He wondered how he could find the key to the garden and then he heard laughter from the other side of the wall.

41:13.000 --> 41:18.000
Then the door opened and a boy ran out.

41:18.000 --> 41:25.000
He was a tall, handsome boy and Mr. Craven gazed at him without speaking.

41:25.000 --> 41:30.000
Colin stood still and looked at his father in surprise.

41:30.000 --> 41:37.000
Then he said, Father, I'm Colin, your son. You can't believe it, but it's true.

41:37.000 --> 41:46.000
Colin took his father into the garden and told him how the magic had made the flowers and trees grow and had made him grow strong and healthy.

41:46.000 --> 41:51.000
Mr. Craven thought that it was a wonderful story.

41:51.000 --> 41:59.000
He sat down next to Mary, Dickon and the animals and talked and laughed for the first time in many years.

41:59.000 --> 42:03.000
He was so proud of his happy, healthy son.

42:03.000 --> 42:05.000
Now there will be no more secrets.

42:05.000 --> 42:12.000
Said Colin, I will never need my wheelchair again. I will walk with you, Father.

42:12.000 --> 42:16.000
They all stood up and walked back to the house.

42:16.000 --> 42:25.000
Mrs. Medlock and Martha watched in amazement as Mr. Craven walked across the lawn, happier than they had ever seen him.

42:25.000 --> 42:38.000
Next to him, with his head held up high and his eyes full of laughter, walked Colin, as strongly and steadily has any boy in Yorkshire.

